# Project 4 — AI Incident Management Framework

## Scenario
NorthStar Financial Services — EU fintech.
3 High Risk AI systems in production. 
No AI-specific incident response capability existed before this project.

## Problem
AI incidents are not IT incidents.
When a server fails — systems go down.
When an AI discriminates — people get hurt, careers are derailed, and regulators must be notified within 72 hours under Article 73.
NorthStar had no framework for any of this.

## What I Built
Document 1 — AI Incident Response Playbook NS-IRP-AI-001 P1 to P4 severity. Five-phase response — Detect, Contain, Investigate, Recover, Learn.
System-specific guidance for all 3 High Risk systems. Article 73 72-hour notification rule.

Document 2 — AI Incident Scenario Library NS-ISL-AI-001.

Three fully reconstructed incidents:
Scenario A — TalentMatch Gender Bias (P1 Critical) 26 months. 140 candidates. The first signal was a single email from Meera Pillai — a rejected candidate. Not a monitoring alert.

Scenario B — CreditScore Pro Model Drift (P2 High) Six months of unfired alerts. Postcode-segment rejection rates 12 points above national average. Priya Mehta's branch complaint as the trigger.

Scenario C — SupportBot Aria Disclosure (P3 Medium) Nine months. 287,400 conversations. Zero AI disclosure on mobile. Article 52 breach. AFM notified voluntarily.

Document 3 — Regulatory Escalation Framework NS-REF-AI-001
Article 73 decision tree. Competent authorities for Germany (BaFin) and Netherlands (AFM). Two notification templates — initial and follow-up.

Document 4 — Post-Incident Review Template NS-PIR-AI-001
Excel — 8 tabs covering root cause analysis, impact assessment, control gap analysis, remediation tracker, lessons learned, regulatory log, and sign-off.

## Most Important Finding
The first signal of a P1 bias incident was a candidate complaint — not an internal alert. You cannot respond to what you cannot detect.
That single finding justifies this entire project.

